\f4\b\fs40 \cf3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Three Critical Settings to Play With:\cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f5\fs28 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 analyser.fftSize
\f6\b0\fs32 : Controls how detailed the wave is. Lower numbers (like 
\f1\fs28 128
\f6\fs32 ) look like a smooth, bouncy wave. Higher numbers (like 
\f1\fs28 1024
\f6\fs32 ) give you a highly jagged, precise wave.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f5\b\fs28 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 getByteTimeDomainData
\f4\fs32  vs 
\f5\fs28 getByteFrequencyData
\f6\b0\fs32 : Time domain creates an oscilloscope line across the middle that jitters with the rhythm. Frequency data creates traditional "bass bars" that dance up from the bottom.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Canvas Styling
\f6\b0 : By setting the background image as a CSS wrapper property on the wrapper 
\f1\fs28 div
\f6\fs32  and keeping the 
\f1\fs28 <canvas>
\f6\fs32  transparent (
\f1\fs28 clearRect
\f6\fs32 ), the canvas line draws cleanly directly over your user's image.\
